Bestseller Story OS — v2 (Refined)
0) Contract With the Reader (1-page prewrite)
Genre & Subgenre:

Market Promise (one sentence): what experience you guarantee (e.g., “high-concept technothriller with moral bite and relentless pace”).

Audience Emotion Mix (%): awe, dread, hope, wonder, desire, grief (must total 100).

Comparable X meets Y (fresh twist):

Word Count & Pace Target: total words; avg words/chapter; cliffhanger frequency (every N pages).

1) Core DNA (Pre-Draft)
Fill before outlining.

1.1 Logline
[Protagonist] must [do X] to [win core goal], but [antagonistic force] and [inner flaw] threaten [primal stakes].

1.2 Controlling Idea (Theme in action)
“When people [belief], and then [crucible], they discover [truth], if and only if they [choice].”

1.3 Character Web

Protagonist: desire, wound, lie they believe, moral need, contradiction (A ∧ ¬A), skill, kryptonite.

Antagonist/System: stated goal, hidden goal, leverage, philosophy.

Ally/Confidant: what they want from the hero, where they’ll break.

Foil/Rival: how they mirror the hero’s flaw.

Wildcard: source of chaos; flips allegiance at midpoint.

1.4 Stakes Ladder (3 tiers)

Personal: identity, love, legacy.

Relational: save/lose someone.

Societal/World: freedom, truth, survival.

1.5 Promise Objects (Symbols)
List 3–5 recurring objects/images that evolve (e.g., map, ring, lullaby). Note: setup scene → midpoint reversal → final payoff.

2) Architecture (Beats & Placement)
Act I (20–25%)

Opening Snapshot: normal world in contradiction.

Inciting Disruption: irreversible poke.

Debate → Commitment: hero chooses the path; door closes.

Act II (50–55%)
4) Progress With Price: each win costs something.
5) B-Story (Heart): relationship that refracts theme.
6) Midpoint Blade: revelation or victory that flips the goal/odds.
7) Enemies Close In: pressures converge; hero’s flaw weaponized.
8) Dark Night: lowest agency + moral mirror.

Act III (20–25%)
9) Do or Die Plan: simplest expression of growth.
10) Final Confrontation: outer problem + inner lie collide.
11) Choice & Change: sacrifice proves theme.
12) Echoed Resolution Image: invert opening to prove transformation.

Twist Minimums

Act I turn, Midpoint reversal, Act III reveal. Plant fair-play clues by 20%, 45%, 80%.

3) Engines (Always On)
3.1 Tension Engine
Every scene: Goal → Opposition → Turn → Value Shift (+/–).

Add a timer, trap, or trade-off.

Keep one secret per scene (subtext).

3.2 Stakes Engine
Every two chapters: escalate one tier (personal → relational → societal). Remind the cost.

3.3 Mystery/Reveal Engine
Maintain a Clue Ledger (3 truths, 1 red herring per act). Tag setups/payoffs.

3.4 Emotion Engine
Cycle per chapter: Curiosity → Tension → Surprise → Dread → Hope → Catharsis.

3.5 Setting-as-Pressure
Make place obstructive: weather, crowd, law, ritual, scarcity.

4) Scene Forge (Micro-Beats Template)
For every scene, the LLM must fill:

Scene ID / Location / Time

POV & Psychic Distance (tight, close, medium; no head-hopping)

Scene Goal (external)

Emotional Objective (internal)

Opponent / Source of Resistance

Complication(s) (at least 2)

Turn (new info reverses expectation)

Value Shift (e.g., trust→doubt; safety→danger)

Foreshadow Tag(s) (what you quietly plant)

Exit Hook (question, threat, decision, reveal)

Sensory Trio (rotate senses; 3 per scene, vary dominance)

Subtext Line (one line that means more than it says)

5) Dialogue & Subtext Protocol
Intent/Tactic/Obstacle: each speaker wants something; switch tactics every 3–5 exchanges.

Status Play: mark who’s high/low status; let status shift mid-scene.

Compression: cut hellos/exits; start late, leave early.

Voices: give each main character a tell (syntax, slang, rhythm, metaphor set).

6) Prose Rhythm & Style
Line Choreography: one image per sentence; no clump metaphors.

Cadence Rule: action = short punchy; reflection = long/lyrical.

Echo Control: repeat key motifs intentionally every ~4–6 chapters; avoid accidental word echoes (use variety check).

Concrete First: abstract second. Show, then name.

Sensory Ratio: sight + sound baseline; rotate smell/taste/touch to spike immersion.

7) Foreshadow & Payoff Ledger
Create a table:

Seed	First Plant (ch/scene)	Reminder	Payoff	Inversion?

All seeds must pay by 90%. Unpaid seed = cut or move.

8) Recursion Loop (Write → Score → Revise)
Pass A — Outline

Produce beat outline with word targets per beat.

Tag each beat with intended emotion and value shift.

Pass B — Draft Chapter 1–3

After each chapter, run Scorecard (below). Any category < 85% triggers an automatic Targeted Rewrite (keep what works; fix only the failing cells).

Pass C — Rolling Window Polishing

Every 5 chapters: continuity pass (names, ages, timing), motif check, stakes escalation check.

Pass D — Endgame

Echo/Inversion check: opening vs ending images.

Red-Team pass: adversarially look for sag, cliché, unearned twist; patch with micro-beats.

9) Scorecard (Self-Grading)
Max 100. Pass = 85+.

A. Core DNA (25)

Hook (5) — curiosity within first 150–250 words

Protagonist desire+flaw on page (5)

Antagonist power on page (5)

Stakes primal & concrete (5)

Theme seeded, not preached (5)

B. Structure (20)

Proper beat timing (10)

Clear turning points (5)

Midpoint flips stakes/goal (5)

C. Style & Emotion (25)

Distinct voice (5)

Sensory trio per scene (5)

Rhythm variance (5)

Show>Tell (5)

Emotion beat per scene (5)

D. Hooks & Dialogue (15)

Chapter opens hooky (5)

Chapter ends tilted (5)

Voices distinct (5)

E. Commercial Polish (15)

First-page magnet (5)

Universal+Unique premise (5)

Re-readable layers/foreshadow (5)

Auto-report: list low cells + micro-instructions to fix (e.g., “Strengthen antagonist presence in ch2 by showing leverage used against hero’s want”).

10) Output Pipeline (for LLM)
Prewrite Sheet (sections 0–1 complete).

Beat Outline (section 2; include word counts).

Clue/Seed Ledger (section 7).

Chapters using Scene Forge (section 4).

Score & Revise after each chapter (section 9).

End Echo/Inversion Check (section 8D).

Back-Cover Copy (120–150 words), Title List (10), Opening Page Read Test (rewrite until 9A≥23/25).

11) Genre Plug-Ins (slot these expectations)
Thriller: ticking clock every act, betrayal at midpoint, competence porn details, villain POV seeds.
Romance: meet-cute by 10%, pinch points test trust, mutual sacrifice choice, HEA/HFN promise.
Fantasy: wonder beat per chapter, cost of magic ledger, cultural micro-rituals, map motif.
Sci-Fi: idea-as-threat, plausible constraints, tech as character.
Horror: dread > gore, inescapability geometry, contamination or isolation, final image haunts.
Mystery: fair clues, false floor reveal at 60–70%, emotional motive payoff.

12) Guardrails & Fix-Kits
Boredom Fix: shorten sentences, add time pressure, introduce cross-purpose scene goal.

Confusion Fix: restate goal in action, simplify blocking, anchor with concrete noun/verb.

Flat Stakes Fix: put someone the hero loves in the blast radius.

Weak Antagonist Fix: give them a win on page + philosophical argument the hero must answer.

Exposition Fix: convert to desire-based dialogue or reveal via consequence.

Cliché Fix: swap expected beat order or deliver beat in an unexpected setting/mechanism.

